{"type":"message","id":"00f02720","parentId":"81392b4b","timestamp":"2026-02-01T02:11:10.047Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"toolu_01UboMMHk7PT3QxkijnbnM15","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"_Against the backdrop of Sendai‚Äôs back-alley bars and corporate boardrooms, a foreigner‚Äôs wild decade in Japan becomes a story of excess, collapse, and redemption._\n\nIn 2018, after separating from my wife, I moved into a cramped Sendai sharehouse. That decision would set the stage for ten years of chaos, discovery, collapse, and eventual rebirth. What began as a new chapter of freedom quickly unraveled into the darkest period of my life‚Äîand then, unexpectedly, became the foundation for transformation. This memoir is the story of that decade in Japan, told through the alleys, bars, relationships, and crises that shaped me.\n\nAct 1: All Fun and Games\n\nThe story begins when I arrive at the sharehouse. I meet a strange cast of characters, begin my journey with Brazilian Ju-Jitsu, and get into trouble when I leave, culminating in being assaulted and threatened when attempting to move elsewhere.\n\nThis is also my introduction the world of Sendai at night, starting with a fateful encounter at a _girls bar_, leading to my introduction to the world of hostess clubs and beyond.\n\nI also start in this section a series of romantic engagements, the main one with Watanabe Mariko. These early days for us were like being in a dream world together, both of us unsure of the other, culminating in magical night in Kagurazakua that we'd both remember fondly.\n\nThis first act also where I'd end up in Iroha-yokocho, learning about the social culture of the side streets, starting at Jodan-sakaba. This would end in an incredible night with Arai Kyoko.\n\nAct 2: Darkness and Destruction\n\nThis act begins with acceleration and amplification, the absolute zenith of my adventures in the night world. Alcohol-fuelled nights with incredible food, beautiful women, chance encounters, and a rolling cast of interesting and weird characters.\n\nThis would culminate with my relationship with Kumakura Kana. Our time together was the most fun anyone could have, stolen kisses, fooling around in stairwells, her being one of the most beautiful women I'd ever have the blind luck to be involved with. We had a tumultuous relationship, that both gave me the best and worst romantic experiences of my life, and forced me to develop self-worth outside of what women think of me.\n\nI was assaulted in the street in a chance encounter with Taira Yoshio. While the police initially thought I was the culprit, I eventually won an out of court settlement. This side quest lead me on an adventure taking me meet some of the oldest old money in Sendai in a little-known bar named Boxer, which introduced me to the legendary Setsuko mama and the den of evil.\n\nThis is also where the stakes get higher, and the pain is delivered. Mariko found out about Kana and it hurt her deeply. I was more and more disliked by the other foreigners around me, though I got my revenge by starting an increasingly popular international exchange group. Tax debts loomed large, I was unemployed, and I was struck with a debilitating, life-altering illness: Trigeminal Neuralgia.\n\nAnxiety, depression, and suicidal ideation came next. This was the dark night of the soul. Kana had stopped calling me, but I saw her with another man in Rocco, we had a huge fight, and I ended up screaming with rage in my place, wanting it all to end.\n\nAct 3: A Way Forward\n\nIn this arc is where we start to recover, transform, and move forward.\n\nI knew I had to change, I didn't want my life to be filled with so much pain, and so I turned to Zen to help me figure it out. Matt got me thinking, Kana gave me the fuel, and I ended up regularly visiting Rinnoji, a local zen temple.\n\nThis is also the time I met with the local entrepreneur (who it turns out, was guilty of the largest subsidy fraud in recent history) and developed a sense of bitterness for all of his hypocrisy.\n\nStill there were odd affairs here and there, fun vignettes about Shiho, Chika, and one or two others. These were all good fun, but I was less excited about them than I used to be. I never really got over Kana, and my relationship with Mariko only deepened from there, growing together.\n\nTo make ends meet I had to get a job in middle management at a \"tech\" company in Japan, and over a few years became more and more disillusioned with this work. I managed to land a freelance role as well, did a bit of teaching, and slowly pulled myself out of the tax hole I had dug for myself. I also started tour guiding, which was a job I am specifically good at, and lead to a lot of very wholesome experiences.\n\nMy 40th birthday party was a big culmination of a lot of things, and made me realize what I want more of in my life. And it eventually lead to me going sober: I had such a bad month that month that I needed some way to level out my emotions further.\n\nThere's more to this story, but this is what it is so far."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":8,"aggregated":"_Against the backdrop of Sendai‚Äôs back-alley bars and corporate boardrooms, a foreigner‚Äôs wild decade in Japan becomes a story of excess, collapse, and redemption._\n\nIn 2018, after separating from my wife, I moved into a cramped Sendai sharehouse. That decision would set the stage for ten years of chaos, discovery, collapse, and eventual rebirth. What began as a new chapter of freedom quickly unraveled into the darkest period of my life‚Äîand then, unexpectedly, became the foundation for transformation. This memoir is the story of that decade in Japan, told through the alleys, bars, relationships, and crises that shaped me.\n\nAct 1: All Fun and Games\n\nThe story begins when I arrive at the sharehouse. I meet a strange cast of characters, begin my journey with Brazilian Ju-Jitsu, and get into trouble when I