hip would just cause chaos and scandal. \n\nThat and there's another girl still there lurking in the depths of my heart, someone I can't shake off, wait out, or drink away the memory of. There's no amount of drinking, fucking, or meditating to get that one out of my system.\n\nWe got in at 6pm with twenty of Ikemoto-sans friends. They were all rough and ready, construction guys with calloused hands and gruff voices, not saying much to each other, just sitting around looking mean. It would transpire that they were all feeling as awkward and nervous as I was sitting next to Airi.\n\nIkemoto-san got Airi up to pour a bottle onto the champagne tower, things were getting underway. We were surrounded by twenty-year-old girls in oiran (courtesan) style kimono, it was cheap and cheerful. We were in bunka yokocho, one of the oldest drinking alleys in Sendai. He ordered very expensive sushi for everyone from a traditional little place across the street.\n\nI went downstairs at the same time as Airi and deliberately sat further away from her as were too visibly \"together\" in the evening so far. She sat awkwardly for a while but a lady that looks like that doesn't stay alone for long in a small building filled with Japanese men in their 40s.\n\nThe oiran girls were all pretty, pleasant to talk to, laughed easily at my jokes. Somehow I managed to convince Mario to take the whole group to Aladdin, a place in the same group with a burlesque show. We got in separate taxis and headed to Tachimachi.\n\n---\n\nThe girl fell on Ikemoto and pretend rode him in cowgirl, the music was some sort trap persian belly dancing remix turned up. Ikemoto was having the time of his life.\n\nI'd been sober for about a month and was trying to temper my nicotine addiction with Rubiks cube solves. I was somehow maintaining a conversation with a tall Italian girl sitting next to me, student at Tohoku university. We talked a lot about what brought her to Japan, some modelling she'd been doing with a local agency, and how much fun she's having working in the night world.\n\nI needed the toilet. This took me past the main floor and dance area. The toilet had a fun poster on the wall, a size chart with commentary on ranges, ranging from \"an exit for liquid\" to \"you are a horse\".\n\nI washed my hands and stepped out of the mens room."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":9,"aggregated":"Mika-san was spinning around the pole, twenty feet off the ground at an impossible angle, an art deco fresco behind her. Her dress shimmered in the light from the mirror ball as her orbit slowed.\n\nA countdown began from three.\n\nTwo.\n\nOne.\n\nShe fell right to the ground, landing right on Ikemoto-san between her legs, the room erupted in applause and laughter. I fiddled with my Rubiks cube and took another drag on my hundredth Marlboro red tonight.\n\n---\n\nToday had been a day. The morning had me working on a freelance project, invoking some dicey lambda functions from a Rails app. Lots of cross-account debugging, moving parts that all fit together eventually. Small progress, hard fought for, the work wasn't flowing how I'd like it to.\n\nThen the whole day managing. Trying to operate with some semblance of normalcy in a Japanese company, the values both alien and reasonable at once. 6pm rolled around and it was time for Ikemoto sans party.\n\nI put on a jacket and a scarf and went downstairs, across from my place. I met eyes with Airi, she was pretty and pleasant as usual, always well put together but vaguely awkward. Airi ran a small seven-seater whiskey bar where I'd met Ikemoto-san. Ikemoto was in his late 60s, a surfer, who'd just sold his company for many millions of moneydollars, and tonight was his big send-off.\n\nWe tried to get in to the venue but were told to come back at exactly 6pm, so we walked back to the covered shopping arcade outside my flat. A few other guests turned up. It felt slightly awkward because it was beginning to look lik